reviews/originality/2026-05-29-not-every-practice-is-a-tool-6243c8e923d5f36f.md:31:Secondary literature gap: The audit did not read Eihei Shingi, full Bendowa or Genjokoan in Japanese, Shinran's Japanese around jinen and hakarai, Tannisho anti-license passages in Japanese, ritual theory in depth, Aristotle praxis and poiesis sources, or empirical studies of autotelic practice and perfectionism. These are necessary before raising novelty.
reviews/originality/2026-05-29-not-every-practice-is-a-tool-6243c8e923d5f36f.md:72:- If: Achievement-driven people benefit from temporary non-result practice. Then: Screened high-achievement participants doing a no-result activity show reduced self-scoring and rumination in the next hour or day compared with metric-free rest or generic mindfulness, without missed duties. Weakens if: The practice increases avoidance, pointlessness, shame, low mood, missed obligations, or performs no better than ordinary leisure. Test surface: Randomized micro-pilot with perfectionism, burnout, depression, avoidance, and responsibility checks.
