reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-the-answer-you-keep-finding-is-already-settled-under-pressure.json:61:      "assessment": "The dialogue materially improved the idea's answerability to a real human problem. It pinned the target problem to rumination, chronic re-deciding, and overproduction in which rework masquerades as diligence and self-worth is tied to producing one more version. It narrowed the cohort to functioning nonclinical adults under perfectionism or burnout, anxious deliberators, and high-output workers. It added explicit non-fit cases, OCD, scrupulosity, trauma activation, depressive resignation, grief, loneliness, coercive relationships, and meaning loss, backed by the Salkovskis OCD-maintenance source, which shows repeated certainty checks can be a stable threat-system symptom rather than a settled answer. It also produced concrete falsification conditions: any rise in checking, shame, avoidance, or missed changed conditions retires the practice for that user group.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-the-answer-you-keep-finding-is-already-settled-under-pressure.json:113:      "argument": "The challenge is to separate three levels: novelty management, research truth, and personal practice. On novelty management, the proponent is persuasive: eight near-duplicates in two days should not be rewarded as eight discoveries. On research truth, the evidence is weaker: a single loop reusing the same frontier, source set, and release-oriented lens has not earned the force of independent convergence. On personal practice, the teaching is promising but narrow. It fits people who are functionally stuck in re-deciding and re-polishing, especially under perfectionism and burnout. It should not sound universal, because many repeated answers come from unchanged fear, social pressure, depression, or compulsive responsibility. The stronger doctrine candidate is not, if the same answer keeps returning, the return is your answer. It is, if the same answer keeps returning, stop counting repetitions and test whether anything real, including the method of seeing, has changed.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-the-answer-you-keep-finding-is-already-settled-under-pressure.json:164:      "revised_claim": "Human problem: rumination, chronic re-deciding, and overproduction, in which attention is consumed by rework that masquerades as diligence and self-worth is tied to producing one more version. Cohort: functionally stuck nonclinical adults under perfectionism or burnout, anxious deliberators, and high-output workers who reopen settled decisions or re-polish finished work. Claim: repeated unchanged answers should lower novelty and trigger a closure test, never automatic closure. A question may be marked settled only when three conditions hold together: no real information has changed; a deliberately different lens does not expose a blind spot; and a bounded act on the answer reduces reopening without increasing avoidance, missed changes, or compulsive checking. The signal that warrants closure is not the count of repetitions but the stability of the result across a changed method of seeing. Non-fit case: this does not apply where conditions have genuinely changed (there reopening is correct), nor to OCD, scrupulosity, trauma activation, depressive resignation, grief, loneliness, or coercive relationships, where unchanged repetition signals a stable threat or pain system rather than a settled truth and where naming the answer settled would sanctify avoidance or pathology. There self-administered counting is itself a risk and clinical guidance is needed.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-the-answer-you-keep-finding-is-already-settled-under-pressure.json:186:        "The practical cohort is narrow: functioning nonclinical adults caught in re-deciding, re-polishing, burnout, perfectionism, or achievement-contingent self-worth.",
observations/claude/2026-05-30-the-answer-you-keep-finding-is-already-settled.md:25:- Modern human-condition grounding: WHO burn-out as an occupational phenomenon and Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, for overproduction and achievement-contingent self-worth (modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing).

