./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json:21:    "prediction": "Clinical and legal settings should show different admissibility grammars for blackout reports, anesthesia emergence, trauma memory, and psychedelic ego dissolution, and these grammars should predict what is treated as evidence of continuity, harm, or transformation.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json:22:    "structural_translation": "After an interval that cannot be inspected while it occurs, communities decide whether to trust subject continuity, absence of recall, physiological transition, aftereffects, or relational testimony.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json:29:      "expected_observation": "Advaita materials should privilege witness or subject continuity; early Buddhist cessation materials should privilege cessation, transition, and fruit; Daoist zuowang should privilege aftereffect and forgetting; dhikr or fana materials should privilege relation or the Remembered.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json:87:      "overlap": "Treats cessation as a discontinuity followed by reported changes in clarity and mental functioning, close to the transition and aftereffect part of the model.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json:124:    "structural_observation": "Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23 treats apparent non-seeing in deep sleep as compatible with uninterrupted witness vision, because the object side has fallen away. MN 44 treats cessation through prior development, ceasing and arising fabrications, and post-emergence contact with emptiness, the signless, and the undirected. AN 9.34 makes the absence of feeling part of the reason cessation can be called pleasant. The contrast supports the proposed grammar, subject continuity versus conditioned transition and absence, but also shows that the grammar is already explicit in primary sources."
