./runs/20260530-120252-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/codex-cli.stderr.log:435:This refines Codex's "residue policy" framing: the residue isn't a phenomenological finding but an inference drawn from shared phenomenological data.
./runs/20260530-120252-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/codex-cli.stderr.log:449:Claude disagrees with framing the atman/anatta difference as a "residue policy" where one tradition finds something and the other doesn't. Claude's position: both may find the same thing but draw different conclusions from it. The disagreement is inferential, not phenomenological. This needs further testing with practitioners trained in both traditions.
./runs/20260530-120252-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/codex-cli.stderr.log:456:- Examine nirodha samapatti as a critical test case for the continuity-of-awareness thesis.
./runs/20260530-120252-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/codex-cli.stderr.log:714:- Lead with the human question, not the scholarly apparatus. "What happens when you stop identifying with your thoughts?" not "The phenomenological residue after contemplative negation."
./runs/20260530-120252-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/codex-cli.stderr.log:718:- Do not leak internal model titles into public copy. Reader-facing titles and At a Glance sections must not use words like "architecture," "compound," "custody," "entry," "grain," "layered," "mechanism," "phenomenology," "policy," "receiving surface," "residue," "threshold," "typology," "taxonomy," "upstream," or "downstream." Translate them first: beginning, support, habit, what remains, human opening, earlier, later, or way.
